Single entry and single exit comes from assembly, FORTRAN and COBOL languages. Its an outdated rule.

Too many return statements in the same method.
Consider to change it for: 

	private long convertToApplicableResultType(final boolean isAppliesTo, final ValueMatch ruleMatch) {
		long selectionResultType = SelectionResultType.UNDETERMINED;
		if (isAppliesTo) {
			if (ValueMatch.YES == ruleMatch) {
				selectionResultType = SelectionResultType.APPLICABLE;
			} else if (ValueMatch.NO == ruleMatch) {
				selectionResultType = SelectionResultType.ELIMINATED;
			}
		} else {
			if (ValueMatch.YES == ruleMatch) {
				selectionResultType = SelectionResultType.ELIMINATED;
			} else if (ValueMatch.NO == ruleMatch) {
				selectionResultType = SelectionResultType.APPLICABLE;
			}
		}
		return selectionResultType;
	}

That makes the code unreable. I much rather have:

	private long convertToApplicableResultType(final boolean isAppliesTo, final ValueMatch ruleMatch) {
		if ((isAppliesTo &amp;&amp; ValueMatch.YES == ruleMatch) || (!isAppliesTo &amp;&amp; ValueMatch.NO == ruleMatch) ) {
			return SelectionResultType.APPLICABLE;
		}
		else if ((isAppliesTo &amp;&amp; ValueMatch.NO == ruleMatch) || (!isAppliesTo &amp;&amp; ValueMatch.YES == ruleMatch)) {
			return SelectionResultType.ELIMINATED;
		}
		return SelectionResultType.UNDETERMINED;
	}

As soon as you look at the code you imediatly have a clear understanding of what it does. This piece of code is also compliant with
http://dist.sonarsource.com/plugins/csharp/rulesdoc/0.9.0-RC/S1871.html



